00:30:07,980 --> 00:30:08,861
It fits really well.

496
00:30:09,281 --> 00:30:09,441
So...

497
00:30:10,242 --> 00:30:17,084
You'll see them get a little more creative with things that don't quite fit in nature, like the horizontal poles from the grappling hook example.

498
00:30:17,104 --> 00:30:22,486
They'll often modify that horizontal pole to look different depending on the temple you're in.

499
00:30:22,946 --> 00:30:28,308
They'll consistently keep this kind of shape on there. It's like the yellow shape on the pole.

500
00:30:29,368 --> 00:30:32,792
but they'll use ways to modify that to make it fit better in the environment.

501
00:30:33,012 --> 00:30:37,917
So it's this kind of struggle to make a prop that is very clear to the player,

502
00:30:37,958 --> 00:30:42,042
you understand exactly what you do when you interact with this prop,

503
00:30:42,543 --> 00:30:45,406
and also make it fit in your world because you don't want it just sticking out like a sore thumb.

504
00:30:47,722 --> 00:30:51,663
And in adventure games, this is even more critical because often you are trying to build

505
00:30:51,723 --> 00:30:55,785
a world, you're trying to tell the story, and you don't want a bunch of repeated props.

506
00:30:56,105 --> 00:31:01,267
You want a bunch of repeated broken rocks just scattered around your game telling you

507
00:31:01,307 --> 00:31:02,027
to solve a puzzle.

508
00:31:02,107 --> 00:31:06,669
You want a very cohesive world that looks like the world you're trying to build.

