00:36:01,594 --> 00:36:05,219
do I do that? This one is moving much faster. Luckily you have a mechanic that slows things

594
00:36:05,279 --> 00:36:10,725
down when it's near it. So the player is kind of building this relationship. They're very

595
00:36:10,765 --> 00:36:13,168
gradually building a relationship of these things together.

596
00:36:17,315 --> 00:36:24,458
I also want to talk really briefly about chunking, which is a psychological process of taking

597
00:36:24,959 --> 00:36:27,860
information, chunking it, and putting it into larger units.

598
00:36:29,141 --> 00:36:33,503
Something that was a big touchstone at Telltale was we never put more than around five things

599
00:36:33,983 --> 00:36:35,684
that were part of a puzzle on screen ever.

600
00:36:36,705 --> 00:36:39,747
And it's because humans can only hold so much information.

601
00:36:40,488 --> 00:36:43,210
We really want them to make those relationships

602
00:36:43,250 --> 00:36:44,391
between the clues they're finding.

603
00:36:44,451 --> 00:36:46,973
So we don't want to just dump a bunch of things on them

604
00:36:47,173 --> 00:36:48,073
and have them find them.

605
00:36:48,554 --> 00:36:50,475
Because that's just as bad as clicking

606
00:36:50,495 --> 00:36:51,476
a bunch of random books.

607
00:36:51,896 --> 00:36:53,518
Clicking a bunch of stuff just to click on it

608
00:36:53,598 --> 00:36:54,939
is just as mindless of a task.

609
00:36:54,999 --> 00:36:57,220
So we want players to be very thoughtful

610
00:36:57,280 --> 00:36:59,962
and think about what is next to each other

611
00:37:00,022 --> 00:37:01,584
and what they're seeing in a sequence.

612
00:37:01,964 --> 00:37:02,945
What's grouped together.

613
00:37:03,305 --> 00:37:05,186
So it's important.

614
00:37:07,963 --> 00:37:09,984
So our next big bullet point for when you build a puzzle,

615
00:37:11,304 --> 00:37:12,865
you have your goal, you've messaged your goal,

616
00:37:12,945 --> 00:37:14,225
you've created your challenge.

617
00:37:15,365 --> 00:37:17,106
The next important thing is giving the player feedback.

618
00:37:18,226 --> 00:37:21,248
You need to let the player know how they're doing

619
00:37:21,328 --> 00:37:22,128
as they play your puzzle.

620
00:37:23,828 --> 00:37:26,509
And you can do that by rewarding and encouraging your player

621
00:37:26,589 --> 00:37:27,550
when they're on the right track.

622
00:37:28,730 --> 00:37:30,831
And you can also do that by communicating to the player

623
00:37:30,871 --> 00:37:31,911
when they've hit a dead end.

624
00:37:32,772 --> 00:37:34,052
These are both very important things.

625
00:37:35,779 --> 00:37:43,647
So it can be really difficult for a player to know when or when not is a valid option to interact with something.

626
00:37:43,667 --> 00:37:47,830
Especially in adventure games, you'll often get the, I can't use these things together.

627
00:37:48,431 --> 00:37:53,576
And it's not great. It means, okay, we didn't have the scope to give you an interaction with this.

628
00:37:53,696 --> 00:37:55,678
But it's still feedback. It's still telling you.

629
00:37:56,479 --> 00:38:00,783
hey, you're on the wrong track. You know, this is like a dart

